nasa climate model : venus was once habitable
according to projections of nasa &apos;s new climate model , venus was once habitable .
scientists at nasa &apos;s goddard institute for the study of space have developed a model for examining venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate study scientists .
the model was designed to determine whether , once on venus , whose surface is hot , without water and sizzling co2 , the conditions could be similar to conditions on earth .
scientists have previously suggested that the low rate of spin of venus can be explained by its thick atmosphere .
but , according to the latest simulations , it appears that venus may once have prided itself on a thin atmosphere similar to earth , while turning slowly .
the model also addressed the earlier topography of venus .
on the planet , the areas were probably drier than earth , but once there was enough water and geographical diversity to rule life on it and provide protection against rapid evaporation .
venus previously also used the sun , which was 30 percent more muted .
&quot; in the simulation of giss venus during slow spin , it exposes its daily side to the sun for almost two months at a time , &quot; explained giss scientist anthony del genio in a new report .
this leads to the warming of the surface and the formation of rain , which creates a thick layer of clouds that act like an umbrella and the surface stitched before too much solar heat .
the result is a climate with average temperatures that are actually slightly lower than currently on earth .
the model set up a story of venus similar to an evolution previously hypothesized by planetary scientists .
although venus was probably habitable in the past -- over several billion years -- it was exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet radiation .
its oceans evaporated and the water vapor was burned by ultraviolet light .
the hydrogen escaped , leaving only a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide with the deadly effect of the greenhouse gas -- that &apos;s venus , as we know it today .
researchers published their results from the new climate model of venus in the journal geophysical research letters .
