kepler measures the speed of turning stars in the pleiades
the latest mission of the kepler space telescope to help astronomers is to get an almost complete list of the speed of turning stars from the pleiades star cluster .
the new data helps astronomers understand why stars in the star cluster are spinning at different speeds , as well as how the turning time is related to the formation of the planet .
&quot; we hope that by comparing our results with other clusters , we will learn more about the relationship between star mass , its age and even history in its solar system , &quot; luisa rebulla , a research researcher at the caltech &apos;s infrared processing and analysis center in pasadena , said in a new report .
the pleiades cluster is located 445 light-years from earth .
many of the stars in the cluster are now reaching maturity and formed about 125 million years ago .
it is now turning the fastest .
in moments of maximum rotation , these teenage stars release huge amounts of stellar wind .
because these winds move along the magnetic fields of the stars , they have a slowing effect on them .
along with the way the star is getting older , its rate of spin is slowing .
kepler measures the spin rate of each star by measuring the time between discovering discernible points on the stars -- similar to the sun &apos;s spots .
according to the latest data on spin speeds , larger stars turn more slowly than less massive stars .
rebulla likens the stars to the dancers , the bigger they make the pirouettes slower than the smaller ones .
&quot; in &quot; ballet , &quot; we see that slower spinning stars are more massive , while those that spin the fastest are usually very light stars , &quot; rebulla said .
because the pleiades cluster is so close , it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing star quality and spin speed .
&quot; the pleiades provide an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions , in both younger and older stars , &quot; rebull said .
there &apos;s still a lot we want to learn about how , when and why stars slow down their rate of spin and so to speak &quot; hang their dancing shoes on a nail . &quot;
rebulla and her colleagues detailed the latest analysis of the rate of turning of the pleiades in three studies , which will soon be published in the astronomical journal .
